    "num": 75,
    "client": "RAD Fire Sprinklers",
    "project": "AI-Powered Sprinkler Placement for AutoCAD",
    "about": "RAD Fire Sprinklers is a specialist fire protection company that designs and installs sprinkler systems for commercial and residential buildings. Their design process involves placing sprinkler heads, pipes, and dimensions on AutoCAD drawings of building schematics — a skilled, manual process governed by complex spacing rules and regulatory requirements.",
    "challenge": "RAD wanted to scale their operations but sprinkler placement on AutoCAD drawings was entirely manual and heavily dependent on skilled designers. When I joined the project, the team was three months past the delivery date and had been pursuing a separate application outside of AutoCAD — using a rule-based approach with some research into image-based machine learning. None of it was working. They couldn't handle multiple floors, exporting drawings into an external application produced poor results, and they hadn't even proved the core concept was feasible. The fundamental problem was that a simple rule-based approach can't programmatically define what constitutes a 'room' in AutoCAD — the drawings are just lines and arcs, not labelled spaces. The CTO was committed to this direction and didn't want to use AutoLISP or build a direct connection to AutoCAD.",
    "solution": "I did my own research independently and found a fundamentally better approach — a U-Net neural network, a model originally invented for medical imaging that takes a 2D grid as input and produces a 2D grid as output. It's the same shape of problem: given a floor plan grid, highlight which cells should have a sprinkler head.\n\nThe U-Net progressively zooms out to learn big-picture patterns like \"this is a large open room\" or \"this is a corridor,\" then zooms back in combining that context with fine-grained detail to make precise placement predictions at each cell. It naturally learns spatial rules — heads go in open areas between walls, are spaced roughly evenly, and don't go on walls or outside the building — all picked up from training on hundreds of completed drawings without explicit programming. It handles irregular room shapes, corridors, and mixed layouts because it learned from real drawings that already solved those cases. The model runs in under a second per floor plan.\n\nThe team and CTO were resistant to abandoning three months of existing work, so I built a working prototype to prove the concept. It's hard to argue against a working prototype when the existing approach has nothing to show after three months. I designed it to work directly inside AutoCAD using AutoLISP — a niche scripting language native to AutoCAD — so the AI places sprinkler heads and pipes directly into the CAD files designers already work with, no export/import steps. I also built an AutoLISP MCP (Model Context Protocol) server to connect Claude Code directly to the AutoCAD terminal, enabling AI-assisted development in a language with very limited tooling support. The project demonstrates both technical research skills and the ability to challenge existing decisions with evidence when the current direction isn't working.",
