    "num": 76,
    "client": "Internal",
    "project": "Project Knowledge MCP Library",
    "about": "An internal tooling initiative to make all project knowledge — wireframes, work items, code, emails, meeting transcripts, and supporting documentation — accessible to LLMs directly within the development team's existing tools (Cursor, Visual Studio, Claude Code).",
    "challenge": "The company was building a complicated integration connecting all internal tools into a custom AI agent portal — it was overengineered, taking ages, and producing poor results. Meanwhile, project knowledge was already documented across wireframes, work items, code repositories, emails, meeting transcripts, project documentation, and extensive API documentation — but developers weren't reading it. Instead of consulting the existing wireframes, work item details, or API docs, they would come to me with questions that were already answered in the documentation. With API documentation alone often running to hundreds of pages per integration, developers would waste time trawling through it or simply get blocked waiting for someone to point them to the right section. This created a constant drain on my time. Meanwhile, project managers were spending hours each day on tedious status report generation, and frequent stand-ups and alignment meetings were consuming everyone's time.",
    "solution": "While the team was deep into building an overcomplicated custom AI agent portal to integrate all our tools, I built a simple MCP (Model Context Protocol) server that looked at exactly the same data — and it just worked. Getting buy-in to abandon the portal wasn't straightforward, but I didn't have to fight that battle alone. People across the company — developers, project managers, even the COO — were coming to me to ask my bot questions about projects I wasn't even on, because it was so much more useful than anything else available. I couldn't answer or research documentation for projects I wasn't involved in, so the demand itself made the case. Eventually the CTO caved and we rolled it out to the wider team.\n\nThere are two parts to the system. First, I created automated scraping scripts connected to all our data sources that continuously pull information and file it under the correct project. This was a deliberate design choice — rather than spending time and money on the custom portal or updating internal tools, I scraped the data out of them, keeping the existing tools untouched while making their contents available to AI. Project documentation and API documentation were a particularly important addition — instead of developers having to trawl through hundreds of pages of API docs to find what they needed, I included it all in the MCP so they could simply ask.\n\nSecond, the MCP servers integrate directly into the development team's IDEs — Cursor, Visual Studio, and Claude Code. The information developers needed was always there in the wireframes and work items — they just weren't reading it. Now instead of interrupting me, they ask the AI, which pulls the answer directly from the existing documentation. Their AI coding agents can also read the documentation automatically, meaning the agents work with full context of the project requirements and API specifications. The system also tells developers based on their code what needs updating against the current requirements.\n\nThis improved developer delivery times significantly — they were blocked far less often since answers to API questions, requirement queries, and integration details were all instantly available through their IDE. For project managers, the system generates status reports on work items throughout the day — cutting out hours of tedious manual report generation and significantly reducing the need for stand-ups and alignment meetings, saving everyone hours of their day.",
