    "num": 77,
    "client": "Fort Bend Women's Center (FBWC)",
    "project": "",
    "about": "Fort Bend Women's Center (FBWC) is a charity providing support services including family support programmes. They regularly apply for grants requiring consistent evidence, outcomes data, and organisational knowledge drawn from hundreds of sensitive documents containing personally identifiable information about service users.",
    "challenge": "Grant applications required staff to manually search through hundreds of organisational documents to find relevant outcomes data, evidence, and programme results. This was time-consuming and risked inconsistency across applications. The core complication was that these documents contained highly sensitive personal information about service users — names, addresses, case reference numbers, and details of vulnerable individuals. Staff couldn't simply hand documents to an AI tool without breaching confidentiality and HIPAA compliance requirements. Internally, I also faced pushback — the company's default process was to build web applications, but the client didn't need a custom UI and I wasn't about to charge them for one. On top of that, the existing documentation tools weren't fit for purpose for back-end MCP design, so there was no established way to even document this type of solution.",
    "solution": "Working with a US-based charity remotely meant managing the client relationship across time zones and cultural differences in how nonprofits operate — their compliance expectations around PII handling were rightly stringent, and building trust that the solution would meet those standards required patient, transparent communication throughout.\n\nI designed and hand-coded the prototype for a privacy-first AI grant writing assistant built on an MCP (Model Context Protocol) architecture with a full anonymisation layer that ensures no personally identifiable information ever leaves the local machine. I initially got pushback internally — the company's default process was to build web applications, but the client didn't need a custom UI and I wasn't about to charge them for one.\n\nThe system uses a ChromaDB vector database running locally to store document chunks as semantic vectors for intelligent search. An indexing pipeline scans their organisational documents, parses the content, chunks it into searchable pieces, generates embeddings using a local Ollama model, and stores everything locally. Hash-based sync handles document adds, edits, and deletions automatically.\n\nThe key design decision was the anonymisation layer using Microsoft's open-source Presidio library, which runs entirely on the local machine. Before any text fragment is sent to Claude, Presidio strips out names, addresses, phone numbers, case reference numbers, and custom patterns specific to FBWC — so the AI only ever sees things like \"[PERSON_1] and her 3 children were supported through our 12-week programme.\" This makes the system fully HIPAA compliant while still giving Claude enough context to draft compelling grant content using real outcomes data.\n\nStaff ask Claude questions like \"What outcomes did we achieve with family support in 2024?\" — the MCP server embeds the query locally, finds relevant document chunks in ChromaDB, anonymises them through Presidio, and returns safe text with source citations. Claude then drafts grant content grounded in real evidence, with no sensitive data ever leaving the organisation's file space.\n\nBecause the company had no process for documenting or delivering pure MCP solutions — everything was geared towards web apps — I ended up creating an entirely new service offering and documentation process for this type of work. That kept the CEO happy as we now have a repeatable process for MCP-based solutions.",
