    "about": "IDM is a marketplace platform for the construction industry — essentially Amazon for building supplies and plant hire. The existing industry relies on established relationships and large sellers who control pricing, making it difficult for smaller sellers to compete and for buyers to get visibility on the best deals across the market.",
    "challenge": "The construction supply market is dominated by large sellers who hold the power in price negotiations because buyers have limited visibility — they tend to buy everything from one supplier for convenience, even when better prices exist elsewhere. Smaller sellers can't break into the market because buyers don't know they exist. On top of this, sellers all manage their product data differently — different naming conventions, different measurement units, different CSV formats — making it nearly impossible to create a like-for-like comparison across suppliers without massive manual effort.",
    "solution": "I defined the product North Star, ran wireframing workshops, and prototyped the AI-powered specification search — the first of its kind in the construction supply market.\n\nThe platform works like Amazon for building materials: sellers upload their product catalogues and buyers can browse, compare, and purchase from multiple sellers through a single basket. Purchase orders are automatically split and sent to each supplier for their specific items — so from the buyer's perspective it's one checkout, but each seller gets only the order relevant to them.\n\nThe AI import matching was a key piece I designed. Sellers upload their product CSV in whatever format they use — no need to restructure anything — and the system matches their products against IDM's curated master catalogue using AI. This prevents duplicates, maintains quality control, and means a seller can be live on the platform in minutes rather than days of manual data entry. The system handles all measurement unit conversions automatically so buyers can compare like-for-like prices across sellers who might list the same product in different units. Full error logs flag any products the AI can't confidently match for manual review.\n\nThe specification search I prototyped lets buyers upload their job specs — the documents that define exactly what materials they need for a project — and the AI parses them, filters the product catalogue to show the relevant items in the quantities required, and lets buyers add everything to their basket in one go. This changes the buying process completely: instead of manually cross-referencing a spec against a supplier's catalogue, the platform does it instantly and shows options from every seller, giving buyers genuine choice and smaller sellers a real route to market.",
