    "client": "Incumbency AI",
    "project": "",
    "about": "Incumbency AI is a case management platform for local council constituency offices, handling constituent correspondence — emails, complaints, and enquiries. The current process across most councils involves manual triage, slow identity verification against the electoral register, and response times averaging around 14 days for 80% of messages.",
    "challenge": "Local council constituency offices receive high volumes of constituent correspondence but the entire process is manual and painfully slow — around 14 days to respond to 80% of messages. When an email arrives, staff have to manually check the electoral register to verify the sender is actually in their constituency (if not, it needs forwarding to the correct one). Then they have to read, classify, and file the message, research the relevant council policies and mandates, and draft a response from scratch. There's no systematic way to analyse the correspondence data — complaints about potholes, climate control, housing — so councils can't easily identify patterns, prioritise issues, or make data-driven budgeting decisions.",
    "solution": "I designed and hand-coded the prototype for a two-part system that automates the entire correspondence lifecycle and turns constituent data into actionable insights for local government.\n\nThe first part handles incoming correspondence. When an email arrives, the system immediately checks the sender against the electoral register to verify they're in the correct constituency — if not, it automatically forwards to the right council office. Then an LLM classifies the message by type (open case update, individual enquiry, organisational enquiry, complaint) and files it to the correct inbox. Within each inbox, the system generates a draft response using an MCP loaded with that specific council's mandates, policies, and local documentation — so the draft is grounded in the right information for that particular council, not generic boilerplate. Crucially, each council manages their own MCP content — they can add, update, or change their documentation at any time, so information stays current and specific without depending on us to maintain it. Caseworkers can edit the draft, regenerate it, or write from scratch — but they're never starting from a blank page.\n\nThe second part is the intelligence layer. All correspondence is saved, classified by topic (roads, climate control, housing, antisocial behaviour) and by geographic area — down to specific streets or neighbourhoods. Council members can then use a co-pilot LLM to query this data, generate insight reports, and identify patterns: which areas have the most complaints, what issues are trending, where resources should be allocated. This makes local politics genuinely data-driven — budgeting decisions informed by actual constituent voices rather than whoever shouts loudest at a council meeting. It also gives constituents a real voice, because their correspondence feeds directly into the data that shapes policy priorities.",
