    "about": "Boodle is a group cost-sharing app that lets friends pool money into a shared pot for large expenses like holidays, dinners, or events. One of the earlier platforms to offer shared virtual cards, it was built to solve the problem of one person fronting costs and chasing reimbursements.",
    "challenge": "Paying for group expenses typically meant one person taking the full financial hit upfront — which isn't always possible for large amounts — then awkwardly chasing friends for their share afterwards, with no guarantee of being paid back. Existing payment apps handled peer-to-peer transfers but had no concept of group pooling, shared spending access, or tracking who had contributed what toward a collective expense.",
    "solution": "I ran the analysis and solution design for a shared virtual card platform that lets groups of friends pre-pay into a common pot before any spending happens. I coded the working prototype to validate the approach before handing off to the development team. The core concept flips the usual model — instead of one person paying and hoping for reimbursement, everyone contributes upfront and the group spends collectively.\n\nEach group gets access to a prepaid virtual card funded by the pot, so any member can make purchases against the shared balance. The system tracks every contribution and transaction — who paid what, when, and against which expense — giving full transparency across the group. Members can request money from others, invite new people into groups, and see the running balance at any time.\n\nThere was a fair amount of R&D involved, particularly around the virtual card infrastructure and the payment flows for pooling funds from multiple sources into a single spendable balance. I wireframed the group management workflows, contribution tracking, and spending interfaces, designing it so the financial complexity was invisible to users — it just feels like a simple shared wallet. This was one of the earlier implementations of group virtual cards in this space, predating many of the cost-sharing features that later became mainstream in banking apps. The platform eliminated the social friction of chasing reimbursements and removed the financial risk of one person fronting large group expenses — making shared spending as simple as individual spending.",
