    "about": "Aker BP is one of Europe's largest independent oil and gas companies, operating five field centres on the Norwegian continental shelf. They explore, develop, and produce oil and gas from deep-sea installations, managing complex subsea infrastructure across multiple production sites.",
    "challenge": "Aker BP's subsea machinery fleet included ageing legacy equipment that lacked modern monitoring capabilities. Maintenance was entirely reactive — either sending commercial divers for costly and dangerous underwater inspections, or waiting for components to fail, which risked production shutdowns and safety incidents. They had no way to predict when parts would degrade or plan maintenance proactively.",
    "solution": "I started with a detailed analysis of Aker BP's subsea equipment fleet — cataloguing the machinery, identifying legacy system integration points, and mapping out what data was available from manufacturers and historical maintenance records. I then ran the solution design process, wireframing the platform's core interactions and defining how digital twins would be structured before we committed to development.\n\nThe R&D effort centred on creating digital twins of the deep-sea machinery — figuring out how to integrate with decades-old legacy systems that were never designed to share data. We mapped every piece of equipment down to individual components, then built degradation models for each part using manufacturer specifications and Aker BP's own maintenance history. These models extrapolate wear patterns into forecasts, predicting when specific components will need replacement before they fail.\n\nThe result is a shift from reactive to predictive maintenance. Instead of sending divers down on routine inspections or scrambling when something breaks, the system flags components approaching end-of-life and lets engineers schedule maintenance during planned windows. This directly reduces underwater time for divers — which is both a cost and safety win.\n\nI designed and hand-coded the prototype for the interface as an interactive exploded-view visualisation of the machinery. Engineers can navigate from the top-level assembly down through sub-assemblies to individual bolts, each with its own degradation model and forecast timeline. It makes the complexity of the subsea infrastructure navigable and gives maintenance teams a clear picture of exactly what needs attention and when. The shift from reactive to predictive maintenance reduces unplanned downtime, cuts the frequency and duration of dangerous dive operations, and extends equipment lifespan by replacing components at the optimal point rather than running them to failure. Processes like root cause analysis that previously took days now complete in hours.",
