    "about": "Wattsight is a London-based AI startup that monitors and diagnoses renewable energy infrastructure. Their platform targets battery energy storage systems, solar farms, EV charging hubs, microgrids, and critical public assets — helping owners and operators detect problems early, optimise performance, and extend asset life.",
    "challenge": "Wattsight wanted to apply digital twin technology and predictive maintenance to renewable energy infrastructure — solar panels, wind turbines, and associated equipment. Like conventional energy installations, renewable assets degrade over time, and specific component wear can reduce overall generation efficiency. They needed a system that could model not just when parts would fail, but how component degradation affected energy output and performance efficiency across their portfolio.",
    "solution": "I was brought onto this project directly by the client, who wanted my specific expertise in digital twin technology and predictive modelling for their renewable energy infrastructure.\n\nI started with a thorough analysis of Wattsight's existing asset portfolio — solar farms, wind turbines, battery storage, EV charging hubs — mapping the equipment, legacy systems, and data sources available. From there I ran a solution design process to define how digital twins could be built from these legacy integrations, and wireframed the platform's core workflows before any development began.\n\nThe R&D phase focused on two things: integrating with legacy machinery that was never designed to share data, and building accurate degradation models for each component. But unlike a simple \"when will this part break\" model, I designed and hand-coded the prototype for the system to show how specific part deterioration cascades into performance and efficiency loss for the overall asset. A degrading bearing in a wind turbine doesn't just need replacing eventually — it progressively reduces generation efficiency in a way that can be quantified and forecast. The same applies to solar panel components where cell degradation, inverter wear, and connection corrosion each contribute differently to output decline.\n\nThe AI insights layer sits on top as an MCP connected to the forecasting, degradation, maintenance, and parts data. Engineers can query the system conversationally — asking which assets are losing the most efficiency, the cost-benefit of early replacement versus running to failure, or how maintenance scheduling across a portfolio should be prioritised.\n\nThe project is still in active development, with the digital twin infrastructure and degradation modelling established and the AI insights layer being refined.",
