    "solution": "I ran the full solution design for a unified farming management platform to replace the fragmented toolset Dyson Farming had been operating across. The operation relied on nine disconnected systems — Epicor Kinetic for finance, Pioneer for dashboards, SOYL and Trimble for precision agriculture, Blackcat, Land Map for spatial data, Fleet Check for vehicles, and separate people and timesheet tools. Farm managers were context-switching constantly with no single view of operations.\n\nI started by mapping the entire operation end to end — understanding how data flowed between teams, where manual handoffs were creating bottlenecks, and which existing systems needed to stay versus be absorbed. The architecture I designed and hand-coded the prototype for keeps the specialist tools in place but integrates them into a single platform, so precision agriculture data from SOYL and Trimble feeds directly into field planning and nutrient management, finance data from Epicor Kinetic surfaces alongside direct costs and budgeting, and Fleet Check data ties into task management and resource allocation.\n\nThe platform spans seven functional areas. Farming management covers the day-to-day — nutrient management plans, fertiliser records, field planning, task management, and stock reporting. Compliance is a major piece given the regulatory environment around agriculture: I designed trading reports, product usage tracking, compliance applications, and a traffic light system so managers can see their compliance status at a glance without digging through individual reports. The reporting layer brings together cropping analysis, nutrient reporting, harvest pack management, gross margin analysis, and audit support. Finance integrates with Epicor to handle direct costs, accounts, input pricing, and budgeting in the context of actual farm operations rather than as a separate accounting exercise. Stock management includes scan in/out with barcode support and reconciliation workflows. I also designed a mapping module for drainage and field maps, tying spatial data to the operational data so managers can see what's happening where.\n\nA critical part of the engagement was stakeholder alignment across teams who had each built their workflows around different specialist tools — farm managers, compliance officers, finance, and field teams all had competing priorities for what the platform should prioritise. I facilitated workshops to build consensus on a shared operational model before committing to the design.\n\nThe key design decision was making everything integration-first rather than building a monolithic replacement. Each specialist system continues doing what it does well, but the platform becomes the single pane of glass that farm managers actually work from.",
